    "title": "Part 3: Model Systems: How Immunologists Think About Tolerance",
    "excerpt": "Part 3 of 6 Model Systems Sections Why we need model systems Case study: Cancer and autoimmunity Why pregnancy deserves a seat at the table Why we need model systemsThe most transformative discoveries in biology have come from finding systems where a biological process is pushed to an extreme in...",
    "content": "      Part 3 of 6    Model Systems                                                                            Sections                                                                    Why we need model systems                      Case study: Cancer and autoimmunity                      Why pregnancy deserves a seat at the table                                                                        Why we need model systemsThe most transformative discoveries in biology have come from finding systems where a biological process is pushed to an extreme in a reproducible way, allowing mechanisms invisible in normal physiology to become visible. In immunology, the equivalent strategy is to study situations where tolerance is operating at its limits. These situations are called model systems, and they are the engine of the field.The logic is straightforward. In a healthy person going about their day, tolerance is working quietly and invisibly. Most self-reactive T cells have been deleted or suppressed via central tolerance. Tregs are maintaining peace in the periphery. Because there is nothing obviously wrong, there is very little to observe from a researcher’s point of view. Instead, researchers find situations where the immune system is dramatically overactive (e.g., autoimmunity) or underactive (e.g., cancer), making the underlying molecular machinery of tolerance much more visible. We can manipulate these systems, remove components, and watch what changes, which ultimately gives us insight into which cells, signals, and checkpoints are engaged or broken.In the study of immunology, two model systems have dominated the field: cancer and autoimmunity. Each has been extraordinarily productive, and each has also left important questions unanswered. In this section, we aim to understand what these models have taught us and where they may fall short and then to appreciate another model system that has been hiding in plain sight.Similarities between placenta, tumor, and transplant models (Boulanger et al., 2024)Case study: Cancer and autoimmunityCancerFor most of the 20th century, immunologists recognized that tumors expressed abnormal proteins that the immune system should recognize, but didn’t. The question of why occupied researchers for decades, and the answer ended up revolutionizing cancer care. Tumors, it turned out, were not simply invisible to the immune system — they were actively suppressing it. They recruit Tregs to their local tumor microenvironment, downregulate their MHC molecules, and express immune checkpoint molecules, together creating an immunosuppressive niche that switches off anti-cancer cytotoxic T cells. In other words, tumors exploit the very mechanisms of tolerance that the immune system uses to protect healthy tissue to protect themselves instead.Video: Checkpoint inhibitors as a cancer treatmentThis insight was transformative not just for cancer biology, but for the entire field of immunology. The discovery of checkpoint molecules that tumors hijack, such as PD-1, CTLA-4, and others, turned out to be fundamental regulators of immune activation in both health and disease. Checkpoint blockade immunotherapy, now approved to treat dozens of cancers and having saved hundreds of thousands of lives, was built entirely on this mechanistic understanding. Cancer gave immunologists a system in which tolerance mechanisms were overactive, manipulatable, and clinically relevant, and the field learned enormously from it.AutoimmunityWhile cancer shows what happens when tolerance mechanisms become too strong, autoimmunity provides a model in which researchers can study what happens when tolerance breaks down. In diseases like lupus, multiple sclerosis, and rheumatoid arthritis, self-reactive T and B cells that central tolerance should have eliminated ultimately attack the body’s own tissues. Studying autoimmunity has allowed researchers to see the mechanics of tolerance failure: the genetic risk factors for autoimmunity, mapped over decades of human studies, revealed exactly the genes that regulate tolerance checkpoints and Treg function.The therapeutic implications have also been significant. By investigating the role of CTLA-4 in rheumatoid arthritis, researchers developed abatacept, a drug that mimics CTLA-4’s T cell braking function and is now a frontline treatment for the disease. More broadly, autoimmunity taught immunologists that tolerance is a continuum maintained by a balance of inflammatory and immunosuppressive forces that can tip in either direction. Cancer and autoimmunity are, in this sense, two sides of the same coin: one reveals what happens when that balance tips too far toward suppression, the other when it collapses entirely.Why pregnancy deserves a seat at the tableConsider what the ideal model system for studying tolerance would look like. It would involve tolerance to a defined, well-characterized foreign antigen. It would be physiological, occurring in a healthy organism under normal conditions. It would be inducible and reversible: you could study the moment tolerance was established, the period during which it was maintained, and the moment it was resolved, all in the same system. It would unfold on a predictable timeline. Ideally, it would be clinically relevant, with natural failure modes that illuminate which mechanisms are truly essential.Pregnancy checks every one of these boxes.Pregnancy is the only known instance in mammalian biology where the immune system naturally tolerates a genetically foreign entity. The foreign antigen is defined: paternal MHC molecules, expressed on fetal and placental cells, are distinct from the mother’s own and recognizable to her immune system. The maternal immune system sees these antigens, yet it actively decides not to attack them. The system is physiological, which happens in every healthy pregnancy without drugs or clinical intervention in every mammal. It unfolds on a precise timeline (9 months in humans, 18–21 days in mice), giving researchers a roadmap of tolerance induction, maintenance, and resolution that other systems do not provide.Unlike cancer or autoimmunity, pregnancy is not a disease. It is a normal biological process, which means the tolerance mechanisms it employs are not compensatory but are the immune system operating as designed, doing something it has been evolutionarily optimized to do for hundreds of millions of years. The maternal-fetal interface has had longer to perfect immune evasion than any individual tumor. The Treg populations there are more abundant and more suppressive than in almost any other physiological context. The molecular toolkit that trophoblasts deploy represents millions of years of optimization.Medawar asked his question in 1953 and framed it as a paradox. It is worth reframing it here as an opportunity. Pregnancy is one of the most sophisticated immunological systems in all of biology, hiding in plain sight, occurring in half the human population, studied by a fraction of the researchers it deserves. The scientists who take it seriously are beginning to find that the answers it contains reach far beyond obstetrics — into cancer immunotherapy, transplant medicine, autoimmune disease, and the fundamental biology of how the immune system decides what to destroy and what to protect. That field is what this course is inviting you into.In Part 4, you’ll see what happens when the exquisite balance described here breaks down, and what the clinical consequences look like for millions of people every year.            ← Previous part      The Immunological Puzzle of Pregnancy                  Next part →      When Tolerance Breaks Down      ",
